00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:46.940
to projects such as this one.

00:09:46.940 --> 00:09:54.310 position:56%
But I confess that I had not planned
to meet so many wonderful people.

00:09:54.310 --> 00:09:58.330
In 2008, with two then
very young daughters --

00:09:58.330 --> 00:10:02.130
and these are my daughters at the
Bancroft ceremony on the completion

00:10:02.130 --> 00:10:05.200
of the book eight years after I
started, so they were quite little

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:07.750
at the beginning; I
decided to write a book

00:10:07.750 --> 00:10:12.740
that would require no
research trips at all.

00:10:12.740 --> 00:10:14.040
That was the plan.

00:10:14.040 --> 00:10:17.730
I had written on Madison
as a law student,

00:10:17.730 --> 00:10:21.730
and I noticed that no one had
written an interpretive account

00:10:21.730 --> 00:10:24.980
of his famous notes of the
Constitutional Convention.

00:10:24.980 --> 00:10:28.500
His notes are the only set
of notes that cover every day

00:10:28.500 --> 00:10:31.260
of the Convention,
beginning on May 14th,

00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:35.440
and ending on September 17th, 1787.

00:10:35.440 --> 00:10:41.020
Every history rely on the notes to
tell the story of the Convention.

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:46.100
But no book interpreted his notes
as if it were a literary text.

00:10:46.100 --> 00:10:49.960 position:56%
So to do this, I needed to first
figure out what the notes had looked

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:54.060
like when Madison wrote
them in the summer of 1787.

00:10:54.060 --> 00:11:00.650
And answering that question took me
seven years, and in an abandonment

00:11:00.650 --> 00:11:05.980 position:56%
of the original no research part of
the plan, and a growing appreciation

00:11:05.980 --> 00:11:10.090
for the notes manuscript
as an artifact.

00:11:10.090 --> 00:11:14.850
So the book is a study of the
notes manuscript as a text,

00:11:14.850 --> 00:11:17.880
and also as a historical
object and artifact.

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:21.760
And the goal became to meld the
story of the notes as a text

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:24.970
with that of the notes
as an artifact.

00:11:24.970 --> 00:11:27.610
American historians have viewed
the notes like many writings

00:11:27.610 --> 00:11:29.530 position:56%
of the framing generation as a text,

00:11:29.530 --> 00:11:31.510
a piece of writing
to be interpreted.

00:11:31.510 --> 00:11:32.810
And it is.

00:11:32.810 --> 00:11:36.260
But the notes manuscript's also an
artifact, that is a physical object

00:11:36.260 --> 00:11:39.200
with a particular history
of composition.

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:42.440
Now, an artifact's something
different than a relic.

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:46.320
The papers of the framers were
actually originally collected

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:47.710
as relics.

00:11:47.710 --> 00:11:50.130
Letters were taken out of
the historical context,

00:11:50.130 --> 00:11:52.480
and they were placed in
collections, for example,

00:11:52.480 --> 00:11:55.080
the signers of the Constitution.

00:11:55.080 --> 00:11:57.500
And this practice resulted
in many papers

00:11:57.500 --> 00:12:00.230
of the framing generation
being saved,

00:12:00.230 --> 00:12:04.010
but often destroying
their providence.

00:12:04.010 --> 00:12:07.730
Now, the marble Madison statue
in this building's foyer looks

00:12:07.730 --> 00:12:10.360
like it symbolizes
the relic approach.

00:12:10.360 --> 00:12:14.070
That's what we tend to think
of when we see marble statues.

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:18.080
But it interestingly actually
emphasizes the artifact approach.

00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:22.210
Sculptor Walter Hancock
depicted Madison as he looked

00:12:22.210 --> 00:12:25.830
in the early 1780s, just
before the Convention.

00:12:25.830 --> 00:12:29.780
And Madison holds a volume of
the encyclopedia [inaudible].

00:12:29.780 --> 00:12:34.170
It appeared on Madison's list
for the Congressional Library;

00:12:34.170 --> 00:12:35.880
and I think it was
volume number one.

00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:39.240
But the book itself is
an artifact with a story.

00:12:39.240 --> 00:12:42.310
Jefferson had sent the book
from France to Madison.

00:12:42.310 --> 00:12:46.290 position:56%
And as I discuss in my book, Madison
used it to study the problems

00:12:46.290 --> 00:12:47.740
of ancient confederacies.

00:12:47.740 --> 00:12:51.710
So the statue tells us
that books are to be used,

00:12:51.710 --> 00:12:56.900
and Madison actually has his
finger holding a place in the book.

00:12:56.900 --> 00:13:00.400
Books and papers tell
stories as artifacts.

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:02.990
And my book was only
possible because archivist

00:13:02.990 --> 00:13:06.040
after archivist made
the crucial decision

00:13:06.040 --> 00:13:09.360
that Madison's papers were
artifacts, not relics,

00:13:09.360 --> 00:13:11.420 position:56%
and that they could be investigated.

00:13:11.420 --> 00:13:17.430
Now, the notes are particularly
intriguing as a text and artifact.

00:13:17.430 --> 00:13:20.030
They've always been
known to be revised.

00:13:20.030 --> 00:13:22.090
Madison made a comment
to that effect

00:13:22.090 --> 00:13:24.860
on the last page of the manuscript.

00:13:24.860 --> 00:13:29.080
In 1840, Henry Gilpin, the
editor of the print edition,

00:13:29.080 --> 00:13:32.820
noted that they'd been
revised by Mrs. Madison.

00:13:32.820 --> 00:13:37.020 position:56%
And the notes even contained signals
that they were used by others.

00:13:37.020 --> 00:13:41.520
Madison wrote in one section that
this section had not been copied

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:43.820
by Mr. Epps for Thomas Jefferson.

00:13:43.820 --> 00:13:48.180
And so the notes have
always been a text that hint

00:13:48.180 --> 00:13:51.190
of their importance as an artifact.

00:13:51.190 --> 00:13:56.450
And you can see I use PowerPoint
the way people use picture books,

00:13:56.450 --> 00:13:59.230
so you just have to kind of look
at the images while I'm talking,

00:13:59.230 --> 00:14:02.230
because they kind of
show everything.

00:14:02.230 --> 00:14:07.050
The book implicitly considers
the classic historical question,

00:14:07.050 --> 00:14:11.620
"How do we figure out how people
in the past saw their world?"

00:14:11.620 --> 00:14:14.380
And the difficulty of seeing
the world from the view

00:14:14.380 --> 00:14:18.890
of the framing generation appears
in cartoons about the founders.

00:14:18.890 --> 00:14:23.000
The cartoons hint at the
unreliability of the paper left

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:25.020
by the framing generation.

00:14:25.020 --> 00:14:30.190
My book focuses on how impossible
it is to escape the distance

00:14:30.190 --> 00:14:34.860
between events and
contemporary recording of events,

00:14:34.860 --> 00:14:39.340
and how important it is for
the historian to recognize

00:14:39.340 --> 00:14:41.720
and consider that distance.

00:14:41.720 --> 00:14:45.990
In particular, the framers
had the opportunity --

00:14:45.990 --> 00:14:49.480
or their widows and their
descendants had the opportunity,

00:14:49.480 --> 00:14:55.630
to curate and revise
their papers years later.

00:14:55.630 --> 00:14:59.030
Now, this is a particular
problem with Madison.

00:14:59.030 --> 00:15:02.710
He left the only seemingly set
of notes of the Convention.

00:15:02.710 --> 00:15:05.510 position:56%
He also outlived every other member.

00:15:05.510 --> 00:15:10.780
This was actually not surprising,
his mom died at age 97 in 1829,

00:15:10.780 --> 00:15:13.920
shortly before his
own death in 1836.

00:15:13.920 --> 00:15:17.910
And as the other framers died,
Madison kept track of their deaths,

00:15:17.910 --> 00:15:22.120 position:56%
and with the rest gone, he got the
final word what historian Drew McCoy

00:15:22.120 --> 00:15:26.110 position:56%
nicely termed "Last of the Fathers".

00:15:26.110 --> 00:15:31.120
So in 2008, I tried to find an
edition that showed Madison's notes

00:15:31.120 --> 00:15:33.800
as they existed in
the summer of 1787.

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:37.920
I actually thought this
would be relatively easy.

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:43.260
But modern editions -- and those
are all images of modern editions,

00:15:43.260 --> 00:15:47.290 position:56%
regardless of what they said,
turned out largely to be the version

00:15:47.290 --> 00:15:51.440
that had been published
by the government in 1840.

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:56.540 position:56%
This edition, prepared by Gilpin,
was based on the transcript prepared

00:15:56.540 --> 00:15:59.750
by James Madison, and
left at his death.

00:15:59.750 --> 00:16:04.220
And various editions included,
at best, selected revisions.

00:16:04.220 --> 00:16:10.040
And you can see the transcript up
there and then the Gilpin edition.

00:16:10.040 --> 00:16:12.310
Fortunately, the Department
of State,

00:16:12.310 --> 00:16:16.560
where the manuscript was
housed in the 19th Century,

00:16:16.560 --> 00:16:19.930
had printed an extraordinary
version of the note,

00:16:19.930 --> 00:16:22.600
largely forgotten for
the last century.

00:16:22.600 --> 00:16:27.940
For this edition, begun in 1897
and printed in 1900, the Department

00:16:27.940 --> 00:16:33.010
of State tried to show Madison's
notes with all of the revisions.

00:16:33.010 --> 00:16:36.490
In fact, a young staff member, John
Weisenhaagen [assumed spelling],

00:16:36.490 --> 00:16:39.980
actually detached the slips
from the original manuscript

00:16:39.980 --> 00:16:41.280
to prepare the edition.

00:16:41.280 --> 00:16:45.930
And he noted in red ink on news
slips inserted in the notes

00:16:45.930 --> 00:16:47.820
where they'd been attached.

00:16:47.820 --> 00:16:50.520
Now, there are some small
errors in this transcript,

00:16:50.520 --> 00:16:55.030
but it remains the best edition
of Madison's notes as it appears.

00:16:55.030 --> 00:16:59.500
In 1914, the government
recommended against reprinting it,

00:16:59.500 --> 00:17:03.080
noting that there were
many sets still unsold.

00:17:03.080 --> 00:17:06.340
But you can -- and I actually
was able to acquire like four

00:17:06.340 --> 00:17:08.310
for almost no money when
I started this project,

00:17:08.310 --> 00:17:11.100
you can now find it online.

00:17:11.100 --> 00:17:14.750
But the edition did not show
the pagination or layout.

00:17:14.750 --> 00:17:20.300 position:56%
And so for that, I originally used
the microphone that was done in 1964

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:24.200
of the notes, and that's now
digitized on the Library's website.

00:17:24.200 --> 00:17:29.800
But it quickly became apparent
that digital images were needed.

00:17:29.800 --> 00:17:34.180
So the manuscript's in
the Library in a vault.

00:17:34.180 --> 00:17:38.760
It's been disassembled, and is
now in archival storage boxes.

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:41.330
The Library sent images of,

00:17:41.330 --> 00:17:45.010
I think what was a
preservation copy apparently taken

00:17:45.010 --> 00:17:47.780
with a Nikon camera, in 2003.

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:50.070
And the images were
labeled "Top Treasure",

00:17:50.070 --> 00:17:52.010
and you can see that on the label.

00:17:52.010 --> 00:17:53.310
[ Silence ]

00:17:53.310 --> 00:17:59.650
The manuscript's 136 and a half
sheets of paper, folded in half,

00:17:59.650 --> 00:18:02.470
four pages of writing each sheet.

00:18:02.470 --> 00:18:04.460
That's over 500 pages.

00:18:04.460 --> 00:18:07.380
So it was actually a lot of images.

00:18:07.380 --> 00:18:14.040
But technology was moving so
fast that by 2008, the resolution

00:18:14.040 --> 00:18:17.160
on these images was
less than desirable.

00:18:17.160 --> 00:18:20.860
Today, current phones shoot at
about five times the resolution

00:18:20.860 --> 00:18:22.160
of the images.

00:18:22.160 --> 00:18:23.870
But digital photography,

00:18:23.870 --> 00:18:27.070
even at that resolution,
made this book possible.

00:18:27.070 --> 00:18:30.140 position:56%
An extraordinary group of
curators, librarians, and archivists

00:18:30.140 --> 00:18:33.690
across the United States took
or helped me take photographs

00:18:33.690 --> 00:18:36.530
of Madison's manuscripts.

00:18:36.530 --> 00:18:40.050
And so as I began to
read the transcript now

00:18:40.050 --> 00:18:43.140
with the digital images, I
realize there were mysteries

00:18:43.140 --> 00:18:44.440
about the manuscript.

00:18:44.440 --> 00:18:46.800
And so let me mention just a few.

00:18:46.800 --> 00:18:50.790
There were visible revisions on the
first 98 sheets in the manuscript,

00:18:50.790 --> 00:18:55.970
but not very many on the last
34 sheets after August 22nd.

00:18:55.970 --> 00:18:59.550
The revisions often were
in the official language

00:18:59.550 --> 00:19:01.820
of the Convention Journal.

00:19:01.820 --> 00:19:06.640 position:56%
But on the last sheets, the official
language already had been integrated

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:07.940
into the text.

00:19:07.940 --> 00:19:11.480
Why? Slips only appeared attached

00:19:11.480 --> 00:19:13.750
in the first two-thirds
of the manuscript.

00:19:13.750 --> 00:19:17.520
And similarly, for the first
two-thirds, Madison had written

00:19:17.520 --> 00:19:21.360
"Mr. M", and then later
inserted "Addison".

00:19:21.360 --> 00:19:26.070 position:56%
But in the last third, he originally
wrote his name out, "Madison".

00:19:26.070 --> 00:19:30.810
There were blank pages in
strange places, like August 22nd.

00:19:30.810 --> 00:19:34.950
One page, September 8th, ended
abruptly partway down the page.

00:19:34.950 --> 00:19:40.770 position:56%
And material had been missing when
Jefferson had the manuscript copied.

00:19:40.770 --> 00:19:44.420
There were also mysteries
noted by earlier scholars.

00:19:44.420 --> 00:19:46.710
People had noticed odd
things over the years,

00:19:46.710 --> 00:19:49.230
but they weren't sure
what the reason was.

00:19:49.230 --> 00:19:53.410
For example, when Jefferson
had a copy made in the 1790s,

00:19:53.410 --> 00:19:56.960
three and a half weeks in
June and July were omitted.

00:19:56.960 --> 00:19:58.950
And Madison even went
so far as to note

00:19:58.950 --> 00:20:02.700
in the margin they
had never been copied.

00:20:02.700 --> 00:20:06.170
And the early editor, Max
Ferrand, realized Madison made

00:20:06.170 --> 00:20:09.070
over 50 insertions
from a set of notes

00:20:09.070 --> 00:20:12.530
by Robert Yates, published in 1821.

00:20:12.530 --> 00:20:16.900
This was odd, because Madison
had openly criticize these notes,

00:20:16.900 --> 00:20:18.370
particularly Yates' claim

00:20:18.370 --> 00:20:21.560
that Madison had suggested
the states might have less

00:20:21.560 --> 00:20:23.140
than full sovereignty.

00:20:23.140 --> 00:20:25.090
But Madison had nonetheless
used them,

00:20:25.090 --> 00:20:27.380
and had actually paraphrased
the insertions

00:20:27.380 --> 00:20:31.380
as if disguising their
place of origin.

00:20:31.380 --> 00:20:34.850
So faced with these puzzles, I
decided to compare the manuscripts

00:20:34.850 --> 00:20:36.690
that Madison and others created.

00:20:36.690 --> 00:20:41.000
And so let me explain
what sources exist.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:43.570
Madison was not the only
note-taker at the Convention.

00:20:43.570 --> 00:20:46.770
Notes exist from ten
other note-takers.

00:20:46.770 --> 00:20:49.070
Many may have problems
similar to those

00:20:49.070 --> 00:20:50.850
that I describe in Madison's notes.

00:20:50.850 --> 00:20:54.380
And Madison criticized some of
these during his own lifetime.

00:20:54.380 --> 00:20:57.280
Historians have tended to
favor Madison's version.

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:00.520
I try to be more agnostic.

00:21:00.520 --> 00:21:03.970
An official record of the
Convention was compiled

00:21:03.970 --> 00:21:06.260
by its secretary, William Jackson.

00:21:06.260 --> 00:21:09.210
It included a journal and
a series of vote tallies.

00:21:09.210 --> 00:21:12.040
And the image shows you the
vote tally on the final day

00:21:12.040 --> 00:21:14.370
when the Constitution was adopted.

00:21:14.370 --> 00:21:16.090
At the end of the Convention,

00:21:16.090 --> 00:21:19.070
this official journal was
given to George Washington.

00:21:19.070 --> 00:21:24.340
And only in 1796 did he deposit it
publicly with the State Department,

00:21:24.340 --> 00:21:27.910
and only in 1819 was
it finally published.

00:21:27.910 --> 00:21:33.850
And Madison actually then used
it to further revise his text.

00:21:33.850 --> 00:21:38.970
But Madison had a secret
copy of that journal.

00:21:38.970 --> 00:21:41.200
In the fall of 1789,

00:21:41.200 --> 00:21:44.540
Madison acquired the official
journal from George Washington.

00:21:44.540 --> 00:21:49.120
Washington's diary is
missing for the dates during

00:21:49.120 --> 00:21:51.750
which Madison would have
borrowed the journal.

00:21:51.750 --> 00:21:56.120
And so we don't know how or why
Washington decided to lend it.

00:21:56.120 --> 00:21:57.910
Madison nonetheless made a copy.

00:21:57.910 --> 00:21:59.960
This is not my discovery.

00:21:59.960 --> 00:22:05.310
In 1930, Charles Keller and
George Pierson wrote a wonderful,

00:22:05.310 --> 00:22:09.690
quite speculative at the time,
article about this journal copy,

00:22:09.690 --> 00:22:12.660
which then was at Yale
where it still is.

00:22:12.660 --> 00:22:16.000
They argued that Madison had copied
the official journal in the fall

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:19.540
of 1789, and he had then
used it to revise the notes

00:22:19.540 --> 00:22:23.280
by including official language
on slips and insertions.

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:29.330
In 1937, Farand ignored the
implications of this discovery,

00:22:29.330 --> 00:22:33.290
and chose to reprint
his 1911 edition.

00:22:33.290 --> 00:22:38.910
And so Keller and Pierson's
article was largely forgotten.

00:22:38.910 --> 00:22:42.340
Yale permitted me to take photos
-- there is no microfilm available,

00:22:42.340 --> 00:22:44.480
and these photos were critical.

00:22:44.480 --> 00:22:48.060 position:56%
There turned out to be small
notations in Madison's journal copy,

00:22:48.060 --> 00:22:52.560
and the notes that suggested that
at one time, Madison had imagined

00:22:52.560 --> 00:22:55.940
that the two manuscripts
would be read together.

00:22:55.940 --> 00:22:58.980
And it was also apparent
that the front page

00:22:58.980 --> 00:23:04.590
of the journal copy wasn't actually
the first page Madison had copied.

00:23:04.590 --> 00:23:10.040
Instead, it seemed, he started
with Monday, August 20th, 1787;

00:23:10.040 --> 00:23:12.750
and that's the image you
can see on the screen.

00:23:12.750 --> 00:23:16.410
That's not the front page of the
manuscript, but it's the page

00:23:16.410 --> 00:23:19.560
that has the title as
if it's the first page.

00:23:19.560 --> 00:23:21.150
Why?

00:23:21.150 --> 00:23:23.440
[ Silence ]

00:23:23.440 --> 00:23:27.830
Thomas Jefferson was responsible
for two other copies of the notes.

00:23:27.830 --> 00:23:31.090
Jefferson had a young man
studying with him, John Epps,

00:23:31.090 --> 00:23:37.100
make a partial copy of
Madison's notes in 1791 to 1793,

00:23:37.100 --> 00:23:41.790
and also a very partial duplicate
press copy that you can see here;

00:23:41.790 --> 00:23:44.220 position:56%
it's at the New York Public Library.

00:23:44.220 --> 00:23:47.920
But Jefferson's copy had
actually additional puzzles.

00:23:47.920 --> 00:23:50.150
Many pages were replaced.

00:23:50.150 --> 00:23:52.560
After Madison's death,
Judith Reeves,

00:23:52.560 --> 00:23:54.860
wife of Senator William
Cabell Rives,

00:23:54.860 --> 00:23:58.710
had helped turn the Jefferson copy
into another one for Dolley Madison

00:23:58.710 --> 00:24:00.200
to use for foreign publication.

00:24:00.200 --> 00:24:03.320
And many pages were
altered to match the notes

00:24:03.320 --> 00:24:06.260
as they stood at Madison's death.

00:24:06.260 --> 00:24:08.380
The untouched press copy, however,

00:24:08.380 --> 00:24:13.060
showed what the Jefferson copy had
looked like in its original state.

00:24:13.060 --> 00:24:16.060
But there were, again,
puzzles upon puzzles.

00:24:16.060 --> 00:24:19.690
Jefferson's copy reflected
an odd division in the notes

00:24:19.690 --> 00:24:23.940 position:56%
between August 21st and August 22nd.

00:24:23.940 --> 00:24:28.580
Epps had never been given the
notes from mid-June to July.

00:24:28.580 --> 00:24:33.900 position:56%
Epps had even noticed that there was
a page missing from the manuscript.

00:24:33.900 --> 00:24:38.260
And the link the account that now
stands in Madison's manuscript

00:24:38.260 --> 00:24:43.810
of the final days seemed too
long to fit on the three pages

00:24:43.810 --> 00:24:48.780
that the press copy suggested had
originally been the only final days

00:24:48.780 --> 00:24:50.830
of the notes.

00:24:50.830 --> 00:24:56.220
Now, we know that the transcript
looked like after Madison's death,

00:24:56.220 --> 00:24:58.450
because Madison left
a transcript copied

00:24:58.450 --> 00:25:01.240 position:56%
by his brother-in-law John C. Payne,

00:25:01.240 --> 00:25:05.300
that was begun basically
after 1818-1819.

00:25:05.300 --> 00:25:11.370
So I began to try and create what
the notes looked like originally.

00:25:11.370 --> 00:25:14.780
Now, I tried originally to
do this high-tech computers,

00:25:14.780 --> 00:25:16.660
and that was a total failure.

00:25:16.660 --> 00:25:19.530
And so I resorted to the
old-fashioned technique

00:25:19.530 --> 00:25:24.850 position:56%
of using colored pencils; [laughter]
something to be said for that.

00:25:24.850 --> 00:25:27.530
I marked the material
copied literally

00:25:27.530 --> 00:25:31.250
from Madison's journal copy;
that's his secret journal.

00:25:31.250 --> 00:25:36.750
I marked what existed when Epps
had copied it in the early 1790s.

00:25:36.750 --> 00:25:40.580
I marked what seemed to have
been revised afterwards.

00:25:40.580 --> 00:25:45.260
And what emerged, obviously
imperfectly,

00:25:45.260 --> 00:25:49.000
was the notes from 1787.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:53.080
Two Madison comments intrigued me.

00:25:53.080 --> 00:25:58.480
First, in late August 1789, Madison
had written to Edmund Randolph

00:25:58.480 --> 00:26:04.280
to make up his opening speech for
Madison; because Madison explained,

00:26:04.280 --> 00:26:07.780
"My notes do not do
justice to the substance."

00:26:07.780 --> 00:26:09.630
Randolph refused.

00:26:09.630 --> 00:26:14.080
He wrote, "He would mingle
inadvertently what I have heard

00:26:14.080 --> 00:26:18.140 position:56%
since without being able to separate
it from what occurred then."

00:26:18.140 --> 00:26:21.660
And so Madison and Randolph
instead sent his original notes,

00:26:21.660 --> 00:26:23.430
and Madison inserted them.

00:26:23.430 --> 00:26:27.090
But why was Madison
comfortable having Randolph write

00:26:27.090 --> 00:26:30.050
up his speech two years later?

00:26:30.050 --> 00:26:35.220
And second, as an elderly man
in the 1830s, Madison reflected

00:26:35.220 --> 00:26:41.080
that his writings during 1790s
might have been too often tinged

00:26:41.080 --> 00:26:43.750
with the party's spirit
of the times.

00:26:43.750 --> 00:26:48.100
And by "party spirit", he didn't
mean party in the sense of fun

00:26:48.100 --> 00:26:51.910
and games; although if you go see
"Hamilton", which I haven't seen,

00:26:51.910 --> 00:26:56.490
I think it suggests some of
the fun parts of the 1790s.

00:26:56.490 --> 00:27:00.380
At the same time, he wrote an
editorial note discussing the

00:27:00.380 --> 00:27:02.960
controversial Pinckney Plan
that had been published

00:27:02.960 --> 00:27:04.260
in the official journal.

00:27:04.260 --> 00:27:07.490
Madison had long thought that
the Pinckney Plan was not the

00:27:07.490 --> 00:27:08.790
original one.

00:27:08.790 --> 00:27:10.780
And for years he'd actually
obsessively been trying

00:27:10.780 --> 00:27:12.080
to prove that.

00:27:12.080 --> 00:27:16.170
And that's part of what you see
on the far right of the screen.

00:27:16.170 --> 00:27:19.020
But in the 1830s, Madison
became forgiving.

00:27:19.020 --> 00:27:22.640
He explained Pinckney might have
used a rough draft with revisions

00:27:22.640 --> 00:27:25.810
that was confounded
with the original text.

00:27:25.810 --> 00:27:29.160
And the revisions might
have been confounded also

00:27:29.160 --> 00:27:30.650
in the memory of the author.

00:27:30.650 --> 00:27:34.070
So was Madison talking
about himself also?

00:27:34.070 --> 00:27:38.520
Might the notes not date entirely
from the summer of 1787; and if so,

00:27:38.520 --> 00:27:42.050
how had Madison actually
composed them?

00:27:42.050 --> 00:27:47.020 position:56%
These questions led me to reconsider
assumptions about the manuscript.

00:27:47.020 --> 00:27:50.690
People have used the notes as if
they were contemporaneous copy.

00:27:50.690 --> 00:27:55.640
But had Madison written every day
in the summer of 1787, and if so,

00:27:55.640 --> 00:27:58.150
why did he always start
with a summary sentence?

00:27:58.150 --> 00:28:01.350
Why did he refer to decisions
that didn't yet happen?

00:28:01.350 --> 00:28:05.370
And why were Saturday speeches
always mysteriously the longest?

00:28:05.370 --> 00:28:09.200
I recall that Madison wrote his
correspondence twice a week,

00:28:09.200 --> 00:28:11.800
and suddenly the pattern appeared.

00:28:11.800 --> 00:28:15.590
In the summer of 1787, twice a
week on Wednesdays and Sundays,

00:28:15.590 --> 00:28:19.810
Madison probably wrote his
rough notes up into a fair copy.

00:28:19.810 --> 00:28:22.750
And if so, how did he
originally take his rough notes?

00:28:22.750 --> 00:28:25.720
He was limited by available
technologies,

00:28:25.720 --> 00:28:27.510
the quilt pen and steel eraser.

00:28:27.510 --> 00:28:29.380
He didn't know shorthand.

00:28:29.380 --> 00:28:33.450
And so he probably used
abbreviations, such as up here

00:28:33.450 --> 00:28:35.890
in a few of his extant papers.

00:28:35.890 --> 00:28:39.200 position:56%
This would have meant that similar
words, like "judicial", "judiciary",

00:28:39.200 --> 00:28:42.980
and "judge", would have been
hard to figure out afterwards.

00:28:42.980 --> 00:28:46.670
Writing from a rough copy explained
the strongest stylistic aspect

00:28:46.670 --> 00:28:47.970
of the notes.

00:28:47.970 --> 00:28:50.320
Madison summarizes the point
of the speech at the outset.

00:28:50.320 --> 00:28:53.760
He created a first sentence that
always summarized the position

00:28:53.760 --> 00:28:55.510
of the speaker or the proposal.

00:28:55.510 --> 00:28:59.090
And so consistent is the style
that you can read the notes

00:28:59.090 --> 00:29:03.070
by reading the first
sentence of every speech.

00:29:03.070 --> 00:29:06.700
It explained why the longest
notes appeared on Saturday;

00:29:06.700 --> 00:29:10.100
not because they were most
important, but because a Sunday

00:29:10.100 --> 00:29:14.110
without any meetings gave Madison
time to decipher his rough notes.

00:29:14.110 --> 00:29:16.870
And so when we wrote about
events on Monday and Thursday,

00:29:16.870 --> 00:29:19.000
he knew what the Convention
had gone to decide.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:21.710
These days were always
written with hindsight.

00:29:21.710 --> 00:29:25.130
So there was always distance,
even in the original notes

00:29:25.130 --> 00:29:27.110
between what Madison
wrote and the Convention.

00:29:27.110 --> 00:29:31.510
From the very first day, he
was revising his understanding.

00:29:31.510 --> 00:29:35.390 position:56%
For myself, it is this
contemporaneous revising that summer

00:29:35.390 --> 00:29:39.880
that is as important as
any of the other revisions.

00:29:39.880 --> 00:29:42.150
Now, a second assumption
needed to be revisited.

00:29:42.150 --> 00:29:44.830
Although referred to as
"notes", they'd been relied on as

00:29:44.830 --> 00:29:48.320
if they had been taken by a
court reporter or a stenographer

00:29:48.320 --> 00:29:50.490
for the Congressional record.

00:29:50.490 --> 00:29:53.460
But drawing on work on
British Parliamentary diaries,

00:29:53.460 --> 00:29:57.160
I realize they belong to the
genre of legislative diaries.

00:29:57.160 --> 00:30:00.880 position:56%
Legislative proceedings were closed,
and what the public had a right

00:30:00.880 --> 00:30:03.900
to was the final product,
the legislation

00:30:03.900 --> 00:30:05.200
and the journal of motions.

00:30:05.200 --> 00:30:08.180
And indeed, the House of
Representatives opens its doors

00:30:08.180 --> 00:30:13.050
in 1789, but the Senate
remains closed until 1795.

00:30:13.050 --> 00:30:14.970
So without published
accounts of the base,

00:30:14.970 --> 00:30:17.360
legislators relied
on private diaries.

00:30:17.360 --> 00:30:19.910
Madison's earlier legislative
diaries are

00:30:19.910 --> 00:30:21.690
in the Library of Congress.

00:30:21.690 --> 00:30:25.340
They're political diaries, and he's
interestingly also revived those.

00:30:25.340 --> 00:30:27.790
And someone could do a
great article on those.

00:30:27.790 --> 00:30:31.750
There's almost nothing written on
them, and also on the Maclay diary,

00:30:31.750 --> 00:30:36.800
which over time has begun to be
seen as surprisingly objective.

00:30:36.800 --> 00:30:40.710
The notes reflected Madison's
political ideas, his strategies,

00:30:40.710 --> 00:30:43.140
the positions of allies
and of [inaudible].

00:30:43.140 --> 00:30:46.110
The original Convention notes
therefore showed what he cared

00:30:46.110 --> 00:30:50.010
about, and they omitted what
he did not find interesting.

00:30:50.010 --> 00:30:53.560
And so they were about
who he found interesting.

00:30:53.560 --> 00:30:56.020
In this sense, the
notes were a biography

00:30:56.020 --> 00:30:58.120
of his view of the Convention.

00:30:58.120 --> 00:31:03.320
They recorded Madison's
convention, not "the" Convention.

00:31:03.320 --> 00:31:07.180
As I reconstructed the original
notes, I found a different Madison,

00:31:07.180 --> 00:31:10.180
a man who desperately wanted
proportional representation

00:31:10.180 --> 00:31:13.780
in both Houses, and wanted to limit
the role in power of the states,

00:31:13.780 --> 00:31:16.990
a man who was frustrated by
the small state's concern

00:31:16.990 --> 00:31:20.740
about Virginia's political power,
a man who left Philadelphia,

00:31:20.740 --> 00:31:23.640
disappointed at the
Convention's failure

00:31:23.640 --> 00:31:27.050
to completely control the states.

00:31:27.050 --> 00:31:30.670
And I found a man who
initiated the dynamic that led

00:31:30.670 --> 00:31:32.870
to the Three-Fifths Compromise.

00:31:32.870 --> 00:31:37.210
Madison repeatedly hinted at a
sectional divide between northern

00:31:37.210 --> 00:31:38.740
and southern states over slavery,

00:31:38.740 --> 00:31:44.140
and he even proposed a bicameral
Congress based on the division.

00:31:44.140 --> 00:31:48.160
Enslaved African-Americans,
of course, would not vote.

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:51.500
And so Madison's plan would
have given voting power

00:31:51.500 --> 00:31:54.420
to states that legalized slavery.

00:31:54.420 --> 00:31:57.190
Virginia, by this calculation,
benefited the most

00:31:57.190 --> 00:32:00.820
as it held nearly 300,000
people enslaved,

00:32:00.820 --> 00:32:05.040
nearly half the enslaved
population in the United States.

00:32:05.040 --> 00:32:07.790
And although after leaving the
Convention, Madison would come

00:32:07.790 --> 00:32:11.630
to blame South Carolina
and Georgia for what seemed

00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:14.250
as an inevitable compromise
over slavery,

00:32:14.250 --> 00:32:17.430
Madison was equally at fault.

00:32:17.430 --> 00:32:21.470
His willingness to embrace slavery
reflected his personal compromise

00:32:21.470 --> 00:32:22.910
over slavery.

00:32:22.910 --> 00:32:25.830
He believed it to be against the
principles of the revolution,

00:32:25.830 --> 00:32:29.480
but he could not imagine a
multiracial American nation.

00:32:29.480 --> 00:32:32.210
He freed no one at his death.

00:32:32.210 --> 00:32:37.480
And indeed, his will left the
profits from the sale of the notes

00:32:37.480 --> 00:32:41.010
to the American Colonization
Society, a group dedicated

00:32:41.010 --> 00:32:45.160
to sending freed African-Americans
to Africa.

00:32:45.160 --> 00:32:51.910
I found a man who was emotional and
aggravated because of his losses,

00:32:51.910 --> 00:32:55.490
but after August 6th, began
to acquire a new role.

00:32:55.490 --> 00:32:59.330 position:56%
And the book argues that by copying
the August 6th draft into the notes,

00:32:59.330 --> 00:33:01.660
Madison grasped the structure.

00:33:01.660 --> 00:33:06.880
So then, a need to reconsider a
final assumption became apparent.

00:33:06.880 --> 00:33:08.800
Who was the audience?

00:33:08.800 --> 00:33:10.440
Was it us?

00:33:10.440 --> 00:33:12.660
Was it posterity?

00:33:12.660 --> 00:33:16.330
Before the Convention, Madison
had shared his legislative diary

00:33:16.330 --> 00:33:17.840
and Congress with Jefferson.

00:33:17.840 --> 00:33:22.610
And on July 18th, 1787, Madison
wrote Jefferson in Paris,

00:33:22.610 --> 00:33:25.170
"As soon as I am at
liberty, I will endeavor

00:33:25.170 --> 00:33:26.850
to make amends for my silence.

00:33:26.850 --> 00:33:30.580
I have taken lengthy notes, and
mean to go on with a drudgery

00:33:30.580 --> 00:33:34.810
if no disposition obliges
me to discontinue it."

00:33:34.810 --> 00:33:38.840 position:56%
I argue the notes were taken largely
as a political diary for Madison

00:33:38.840 --> 00:33:42.550 position:56%
and Jefferson, and that they're part
of the histories told of Madison

00:33:42.550 --> 00:33:44.010
and Jefferson as collaborators.

00:33:44.010 --> 00:33:45.570
[ Silence ]

00:33:45.570 --> 00:33:48.790
With this, the boundary of the
original notes began to shift.

00:33:48.790 --> 00:33:52.130
Madison's integration of
large sections of text

00:33:52.130 --> 00:33:54.660
from the journal copy
in the latter section

00:33:54.660 --> 00:33:57.380
of the notes raised the possibility

00:33:57.380 --> 00:34:01.740
that Madison had written
this section after 1789.

00:34:01.740 --> 00:34:06.760
Could the manuscript
offer additional evidence?

00:34:06.760 --> 00:34:10.310
Watermarks have long been
a story of the Convention.

00:34:10.310 --> 00:34:13.010
Watermarks were used to prove

00:34:13.010 --> 00:34:17.950
that the Charles Pinckney Plan was
not written in the summer of 1787.

00:34:17.950 --> 00:34:20.730
And watermarks were used
to disprove a contention

00:34:20.730 --> 00:34:23.850
by Professor William Crosskey
of the University of Chicago

00:34:23.850 --> 00:34:27.750
that Madison wrote
sections in the 1820s.

00:34:27.750 --> 00:34:29.050
Now, it's important to realized

00:34:29.050 --> 00:34:31.460
that watermarks are only
corroborating evidence.

00:34:31.460 --> 00:34:34.650
Nothing in the book
exclusively relies on them;

00:34:34.650 --> 00:34:37.690
because their presence has
an almost infinite number

00:34:37.690 --> 00:34:40.410
of alternative explanations.

00:34:40.410 --> 00:34:44.750
But here they reinforce
the textual evidence.

00:34:44.750 --> 00:34:46.530
Older technology made it difficult

00:34:46.530 --> 00:34:48.810
to obtain enough images
to study differences.

00:34:48.810 --> 00:34:53.140
And so the Library generously
took photographs of watermarks.

00:34:53.140 --> 00:34:55.240
I classified them in the Library,

00:34:55.240 --> 00:34:59.170
put the notes on a light
table for us to check.

00:34:59.170 --> 00:35:01.780
Madison was interestingly
consistent.

00:35:01.780 --> 00:35:08.210
Between May 1787 and August 21st,
the paper's almost entirely paper

00:35:08.210 --> 00:35:10.960
with marks associated
with James Whatman.

00:35:10.960 --> 00:35:16.560 position:56%
And this paper matches precisely the
letters Madison wrote this summer.

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:21.990
But it appears in the notes
after August 21st only

00:35:21.990 --> 00:35:27.170
in the plan appended to the
manuscript written about Hamilton.

00:35:27.170 --> 00:35:30.460
Decidedly different
Whatman paper was used

00:35:30.460 --> 00:35:33.330
for the section begging
with August 22nd.

00:35:33.330 --> 00:35:39.430
This paper does not match any
extant letter from the summer.

00:35:39.430 --> 00:35:42.660
Other evidence corroborates
the division.

00:35:42.660 --> 00:35:47.060
The holes used to sew the
August 22nd section differ,

00:35:47.060 --> 00:35:50.030
the division matches the
division that was there

00:35:50.030 --> 00:35:53.930
in the Jefferson copy,
it corresponds roughly

00:35:53.930 --> 00:35:57.320
to where Madison began
his secret journal copy,

00:35:57.320 --> 00:36:01.850
and it matches precisely the
shift from the later insertion

00:36:01.850 --> 00:36:03.870
of journal language in the notes

00:36:03.870 --> 00:36:06.830
to original integration
of that language.

00:36:06.830 --> 00:36:11.510
And this is the watermark -- two
of the crucial Whatman watermarks.

00:36:11.510 --> 00:36:14.140
[ Silence ]

00:36:14.140 --> 00:36:16.720
The book therefore,
argues that the notes

00:36:16.720 --> 00:36:19.960
after August 21st represent
an unconformity,

00:36:19.960 --> 00:36:22.120
a missing section of time.

00:36:22.120 --> 00:36:24.790
The evidence from the text
and artifact tell a new story

00:36:24.790 --> 00:36:26.270
about Madison and the Convention.

00:36:26.270 --> 00:36:28.350
Madison became sick that week,

00:36:28.350 --> 00:36:31.150
something that he was
susceptible to under stress.

00:36:31.150 --> 00:36:33.690 position:56%
And the delegates sent controversial
issues to the committee.

00:36:33.690 --> 00:36:35.910
And for the first time,
Madison served

00:36:35.910 --> 00:36:38.510
on the three-most important
committees.

00:36:38.510 --> 00:36:43.100
He was too involved in drafting to
bother writing up his rough notes.

00:36:43.100 --> 00:36:47.010
And it may have been impossible
for him to disentangle decisions

00:36:47.010 --> 00:36:49.670
and committees from those
on the Convention floors.

00:36:49.670 --> 00:36:52.490
So at the very moment that
the Convention decided many

00:36:52.490 --> 00:36:55.600
of the issues we debate
today, congressional powers,

00:36:55.600 --> 00:36:59.470
presidential powers,
impeachment, the electoral college,

00:36:59.470 --> 00:37:01.920
the notes are the most unreliable.

00:37:01.920 --> 00:37:04.370
But the collapse of
the notes represents

00:37:04.370 --> 00:37:08.660
and reflects the contemporary
inability of the delegates

00:37:08.660 --> 00:37:10.600
to see the final Constitution

00:37:10.600 --> 00:37:13.470
in the sense we mistakenly
imagine they could.

00:37:13.470 --> 00:37:17.930
Between 1787 and 1789,
the Convention's relevance

00:37:17.930 --> 00:37:20.330
and Madison's understanding
of it changed.

00:37:20.330 --> 00:37:22.390
He wrote the federalist essays.

00:37:22.390 --> 00:37:25.490
He made arguments in the
Virginia Ratification Convention.

00:37:25.490 --> 00:37:30.510
He understood the textual ambiguity
of the Constitution when we served

00:37:30.510 --> 00:37:32.150
in the first Congress,

00:37:32.150 --> 00:37:35.420
and he proposed amendments
to the Constitution.

00:37:35.420 --> 00:37:39.260
Madison wanted the
amendments interwoven

00:37:39.260 --> 00:37:40.830
with the original Constitution.

00:37:40.830 --> 00:37:45.310
But Roger Sherman insisted
that they be supplemental.

00:37:45.310 --> 00:37:48.560
Sherman spoke of a
sacred Constitution

00:37:48.560 --> 00:37:52.670
to which the amendments should
be added, and Congress agreed.

00:37:52.670 --> 00:37:57.390
And so only with that decision
in 1789, did it become clear

00:37:57.390 --> 00:38:00.120
that the text of the Constitution,

00:38:00.120 --> 00:38:05.540
and the work of the Convention
would remain forever intact.

00:38:05.540 --> 00:38:09.330
And so now, suddenly, Madison's
notes had a new potentially

00:38:09.330 --> 00:38:12.910
significant relevance.

00:38:12.910 --> 00:38:14.540
With Jefferson about to return,

00:38:14.540 --> 00:38:17.210
Madison completes his
incomplete notes.

00:38:17.210 --> 00:38:19.060
He makes the copy of
the official journal.

00:38:19.060 --> 00:38:23.600
He uses it to make sense of
whatever rough notes he still had,

00:38:23.600 --> 00:38:27.270
far more than the original
sections of the notes.

00:38:27.270 --> 00:38:31.810
The post-August 21st notes
focused on textual changes

00:38:31.810 --> 00:38:34.540 position:56%
to the Constitution and the reasons.

00:38:34.540 --> 00:38:36.630
Now, there were undoubtedly
other changes

00:38:36.630 --> 00:38:38.990
that are impossible to
know with precision.

00:38:38.990 --> 00:38:42.430
How had Madison's perspective
changed over two years?

00:38:42.430 --> 00:38:46.610
I speculate in the book about
whether he spoke the statements

00:38:46.610 --> 00:38:50.430
against slavery on August 25th
that he attributes to himself.

00:38:50.430 --> 00:38:55.250
No one else ever recorded him
saying anything against slavery.

00:38:55.250 --> 00:38:59.920
And his words bear a marked
resemblance to those he recorded

00:38:59.920 --> 00:39:02.330
of Luther Martin on August 21st.

00:39:02.330 --> 00:39:03.630
Was it coincidence?

00:39:03.630 --> 00:39:08.740
Did he have remaining rough notes
containing his remarks, or in 1789,

00:39:08.740 --> 00:39:12.350
1790, did he decide to ensure

00:39:12.350 --> 00:39:17.820 position:56%
that the notes reflected what he
now understood surely must have been

00:39:17.820 --> 00:39:19.120
his position?

00:39:19.120 --> 00:39:24.250
The book suggests that in the years
immediately after the Convention,

00:39:24.250 --> 00:39:29.090 position:56%
Madison also likely replaced several
sheets containing his speeches

00:39:29.090 --> 00:39:30.960
as his perspective changed.

00:39:30.960 --> 00:39:33.660
In some respects, this
is not surprising.

00:39:33.660 --> 00:39:37.650
One cannot take notes
of one's self speaking.

00:39:37.650 --> 00:39:42.280
And so Madison's own speeches,
even those he wrote down in 1787,

00:39:42.280 --> 00:39:45.460
are the most contested
in terms of reliability.

00:39:45.460 --> 00:39:49.890
And he may therefore have been
the most comfortable altering them

00:39:49.890 --> 00:39:55.530
as his understanding of what he
had been attempting to say changed.

00:39:55.530 --> 00:39:56.830
These sheets were identified

00:39:56.830 --> 00:39:59.530
because the watermarks do not
match the surrounding pages,

00:39:59.530 --> 00:40:02.660
and there was corroborating
textual evidence.

00:40:02.660 --> 00:40:06.240
Once that relates to June 6th
through 8th, and it fits the story

00:40:06.240 --> 00:40:10.180 position:56%
about Madison's initial difficulties
in taking notes, and the chronology

00:40:10.180 --> 00:40:12.080
around federalist [inaudible].

00:40:12.080 --> 00:40:16.390
A second set relates to Jefferson.

00:40:16.390 --> 00:40:20.040
Jefferson returned from
Paris in the fall of 1789.

00:40:20.040 --> 00:40:22.860
The "Hamilton" musical has
that song, "What Did I Miss,"

00:40:22.860 --> 00:40:24.750
which pretty much sums
up the whole thing.

00:40:24.750 --> 00:40:27.510
[Laughter] And he saw the
world through the lens

00:40:27.510 --> 00:40:29.710 position:56%
of the French Revolution; supporters

00:40:29.710 --> 00:40:32.340
of Republican government,
versus monarchists.

00:40:32.340 --> 00:40:34.820 position:56%
And he became obsessed with the idea

00:40:34.820 --> 00:40:40.570 position:56%
that Alexander Hamilton was a secret
monarchist, in part based on reading

00:40:40.570 --> 00:40:44.420
about Hamilton's June
speech in Madison's notes.

00:40:44.420 --> 00:40:48.640 position:56%
Four sheets in the manuscript appear
related to Jefferson's promotion

00:40:48.640 --> 00:40:50.440
of Republican government.

00:40:50.440 --> 00:40:54.300
And one finds this phrase
more prevalent on these pages.

00:40:54.300 --> 00:40:59.260
A related replaced sheet relates to
a vote by the Virginia delegation

00:40:59.260 --> 00:41:04.950
in favor of an executive
with life tenure,

00:41:04.950 --> 00:41:07.500
the president on life tenure,

00:41:07.500 --> 00:41:12.960 position:56%
a position that after the Convention
looked suspiciously like a monarch,

00:41:12.960 --> 00:41:15.860
and had become aligned
with Hamilton.

00:41:15.860 --> 00:41:19.160
The sheets containing
this first speech,

00:41:19.160 --> 00:41:23.270
and the final Virginia vote
match precisely the section

00:41:23.270 --> 00:41:26.260
that Jefferson never
was able to copy.

00:41:26.260 --> 00:41:28.620
And so I suggest that
Madison was working

00:41:28.620 --> 00:41:31.950
on replacing these
sheets in the 1790s.

00:41:31.950 --> 00:41:34.700
Now, I didn't have sufficient
evidence precisely date

00:41:34.700 --> 00:41:38.210
and explain two other
sets of replaced sets.

00:41:38.210 --> 00:41:41.640
Madison was not happy with
something on September 7th or 8th.

00:41:41.640 --> 00:41:42.940
He replaced that sheet.

00:41:42.940 --> 00:41:45.400
He messed something
up in replacing it.

00:41:45.400 --> 00:41:50.350
Perhaps notices there's something
missing, Madison subsequently adds

00:41:50.350 --> 00:41:54.580
that material in an awkward
way back into the manuscript.

00:41:54.580 --> 00:41:57.250
And similarly, I speculate
that the final two days

00:41:57.250 --> 00:41:59.270
of the Convention might
have been written

00:41:59.270 --> 00:42:00.770
at a slightly different time,

00:42:00.770 --> 00:42:05.810 position:56%
and they may have replaced a
shorter original conclusion that was

00:42:05.810 --> 00:42:08.600
in place when Jefferson's
copy was made.

00:42:08.600 --> 00:42:11.280
But I'm not at all certain of this.

00:42:11.280 --> 00:42:15.010 position:56%
History should be about
interpretation and reinterpretation.

00:42:15.010 --> 00:42:18.890
And so I put the evidence
in a set of appendices,

00:42:18.890 --> 00:42:22.040
the evidence that discusses the
manuscripts and includes a list

00:42:22.040 --> 00:42:24.470
of the sheets and slips with
the watermark information

00:42:24.470 --> 00:42:26.330
as I was able to develop it.

00:42:26.330 --> 00:42:29.930
And I'm sure my book will
not be the last word.

00:42:29.930 --> 00:42:34.690
By 1796, the final sheets
were likely in place.

00:42:34.690 --> 00:42:37.230
And in December 1796,

00:42:37.230 --> 00:42:39.900
Madison announced his
retirement from politics.

00:42:39.900 --> 00:42:43.920
And that same month, Jefferson
became vice president.

00:42:43.920 --> 00:42:47.040
Jefferson viewed the notes as
part of his political agenda,

00:42:47.040 --> 00:42:50.950
and he urged publication, arguing,

00:42:50.950 --> 00:42:55.790
"The Constitution will then
receive a different explanation."

00:42:55.790 --> 00:42:57.420
Jefferson believed publication

00:42:57.420 --> 00:43:00.760
of the notes would undermine
the Adams administration.

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:03.010
Madison demurred.

00:43:03.010 --> 00:43:06.870
He worried that Jefferson had
not read the entire notes;

00:43:06.870 --> 00:43:09.230
and he might have been
right about that.

00:43:09.230 --> 00:43:11.990
And he worried that the notes
would not support Jefferson's

00:43:11.990 --> 00:43:17.470
interpretation, and worse, that
other reports would perhaps be made

00:43:17.470 --> 00:43:20.480
out in muster, and they
would not necessarily confirm

00:43:20.480 --> 00:43:21.780
Madison's version.

00:43:21.780 --> 00:43:25.520
He worried, "What turn might
be giving the impression

00:43:25.520 --> 00:43:27.380
on the public mind?"

00:43:27.380 --> 00:43:29.910
Nothing in the notes would
damage Jefferson's reputation,

00:43:29.910 --> 00:43:34.330
but for Madison, the expediency of
publication weighed differently.

00:43:34.330 --> 00:43:37.630
Madison's concerns triumphed;
the notes were never published.

00:43:37.630 --> 00:43:41.550 position:56%
And Jefferson moved onto a different
interpretation of the Constitution,

00:43:41.550 --> 00:43:46.320 position:56%
one in which was a compact among
the states, and perhaps with relief,

00:43:46.320 --> 00:43:49.430
Madison put the notes away.

00:43:49.430 --> 00:43:54.220
After retiring from the presidency
in 1817, Madison continued

00:43:54.220 --> 00:43:58.600
to revise the notes to increase the
appearance of comprehensiveness.

00:43:58.600 --> 00:44:01.250
He added revisions from
the official journal.

00:44:01.250 --> 00:44:04.920
He inserted missing sections
of speeches that he paraphrased

00:44:04.920 --> 00:44:06.890
from Yates' notes, and then he

00:44:06.890 --> 00:44:11.500
and his brother-in-law created a
transcript with selected letters

00:44:11.500 --> 00:44:14.300
to explain the larger context.

00:44:14.300 --> 00:44:18.950
But though he repeatedly flirted
with publication, he refrained.

00:44:18.950 --> 00:44:23.550
I believe he continually
worried about other accounts.

00:44:23.550 --> 00:44:30.850
Not until 1827-1828 did the other
three significant note-takers,

00:44:30.850 --> 00:44:34.200
Rufus King of Massachusetts,
John Lansing of New York,

00:44:34.200 --> 00:44:37.670
and the Secretary William
Jackson die.

00:44:37.670 --> 00:44:42.490
Only in 1829 was Madison
the only living member left.

00:44:42.490 --> 00:44:47.940
And by that point, he settled
on postromous publication.

00:44:47.940 --> 00:44:52.430
Madison's will left the
notes to Dolley Madison.

00:44:52.430 --> 00:44:57.880
And Congress finally agreed
to buy the papers for $30,000.

00:44:57.880 --> 00:45:00.410
In 1840, Madison's
notes were published

00:45:00.410 --> 00:45:02.780
in a three-volume collection
of his papers.

00:45:02.780 --> 00:45:08.330
Now, in the introduction, a single
description of Madison's writing

00:45:08.330 --> 00:45:13.280
of the notes reassured readers
of the contemporaneous accuracy.

00:45:13.280 --> 00:45:17.820
And this description's been
repeated by countless historians.

00:45:17.820 --> 00:45:22.600
But intriguingly, Madison
never wrote in his own hand;

00:45:22.600 --> 00:45:25.990
that the notes in their entirety
had been written that summer.

00:45:25.990 --> 00:45:30.970
I tracked down the original
version of that introduction.

00:45:30.970 --> 00:45:33.790
And the sentence breaks,

00:45:33.790 --> 00:45:37.160
and the final assertion
is in Dolly's handwriting.

00:45:37.160 --> 00:45:41.520
And you can see that
there with Dolly's --

00:45:41.520 --> 00:45:47.100
the introduction sentence with the
italics being Dolly's handwriting.

00:45:47.100 --> 00:45:51.950 position:56%
Madison may have consented to the
edition, for his handwriting appears

00:45:51.950 --> 00:45:58.920
as an insertion on the sheet; but
he never actually wrote it himself.

00:45:58.920 --> 00:46:01.640
He had never settled on
a precise explanation

00:46:01.640 --> 00:46:05.690
of the notes' relationship
to the Convention.

00:46:05.690 --> 00:46:10.330 position:56%
Madison understood his revisions as
repeated efforts to create a record,

00:46:10.330 --> 00:46:14.660
his record of what he saw
significant in the Convention.

00:46:14.660 --> 00:46:17.910
Yet each revision, small and large,

00:46:17.910 --> 00:46:21.930
increased the distance
from the summer of 1787.

00:46:21.930 --> 00:46:26.260
Over the years and decades, words,
concepts, compromises, shifted

00:46:26.260 --> 00:46:27.950
and took on new political meanings.

00:46:27.950 --> 00:46:31.800
And motivations were
disputed, and context was lost.

00:46:31.800 --> 00:46:35.970
The Convention could not see the
Constitution until the final days,

00:46:35.970 --> 00:46:40.610 position:56%
and from the moment the Constitution
became visible, it was contested.

00:46:40.610 --> 00:46:43.630
I believe that the
revisions do not detract,

00:46:43.630 --> 00:46:47.960
but rather enhance the
manuscript's significance.

00:46:47.960 --> 00:46:49.750
The story of Madison's composition

00:46:49.750 --> 00:46:53.560
of the notes emphasizes
his inability and that

00:46:53.560 --> 00:46:58.240
of his fellow delegates to
perceive the extraordinary document

00:46:58.240 --> 00:47:01.330
that the Constitution would become.

00:47:01.330 --> 00:47:04.950 position:56%
And so tracing Madison's composition
of the notes guides us back

00:47:04.950 --> 00:47:07.250
to a moment when the
substance and fate

00:47:07.250 --> 00:47:10.310
of the Constitution
remained uncertain.

00:47:10.310 --> 00:47:12.310
Madison's narrative in
the notes was always

00:47:12.310 --> 00:47:16.030
that of James Madison, a member.

00:47:16.030 --> 00:47:19.850
Beginning in 1787 and
continuing for a half century,

00:47:19.850 --> 00:47:23.590
he struggled to understand
what had happened that summer,

00:47:23.590 --> 00:47:26.900
a struggle that continues
into our own day.

00:47:26.900 --> 00:47:29.360
It's been a great privilege
to speak here today.

00:47:29.360 --> 00:47:31.510
Thank you very much.

