and they're mostly in dissents.

00:53:50.500 --> 00:53:54.200
So it doesn't matter that
much in that respect,

00:53:54.200 --> 00:53:56.220
in terms of pure citation.

00:53:56.220 --> 00:54:00.450
I think the place that the book
will give people some difficulty is

00:54:00.450 --> 00:54:06.020
that even though they're not
cited, many of the understandings

00:54:06.020 --> 00:54:10.340 position:56%
that the Court has held with respect
to the Constitution recently rely

00:54:10.340 --> 00:54:15.100
on a belief that in Philadelphia
in August and September,

00:54:15.100 --> 00:54:17.720
the people who wrote the
Constitution understood the

00:54:17.720 --> 00:54:22.000
Constitution in all the
complicated ways that we do.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:25.880
And my book sort of argues
they didn't; that they were

00:54:25.880 --> 00:54:29.190
so busy drafting it and
trying to put it together

00:54:29.190 --> 00:54:32.670
that they understood
the basic structures,

00:54:32.670 --> 00:54:35.600
but the very fine-tuned
way that the Court has come

00:54:35.600 --> 00:54:40.990
to read the Constitution
makes sense 225 years later,

00:54:40.990 --> 00:54:43.610
but it might not have
made sense to them.

00:54:43.610 --> 00:54:46.470
But the Court's very
tricky about that.

00:54:46.470 --> 00:54:47.770
Yes, sir?

00:54:47.770 --> 00:54:59.860
&gt;&gt; I'd like to ask another
